                <head>66. Summary of Conclusions of a Washington Special Actions Group Meeting<note
                        n="1" type="source" xml:id="d66fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName
                            corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss>
                        Institutional Files (H-Files), Box H–116, Washington Special Actions Group,
                            <gloss target="#t_WSAG1">WSAG</gloss> Minutes (Originals) 1–3–72 to
                        7–24–72. Top Secret; Sensitive. The meeting took place in the White House
                        Situation Room.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            from="1972-04-06T09:54:00-05:00" to="1972-04-06T10:20:00-05:00">April 6,
                            1972, 9:54–10:20 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Vietnam</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>Chairman</item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Henry A. Kissinger</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>State</item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName>John N. Irwin</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_SWH1">William Sullivan</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Defense</item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_RK1">Kenneth Rush</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_NGW1">Warren Nutter</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>R/Adm. <persName>William R. Flanagan</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss>
                    </item>
                    <item>Adm. <persName corresp="#p_MTH1">Thomas H. Moorer</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HRM1">Richard Helms</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName>William Newton</persName> (for Mr. <persName
                            corresp="#p_HRM1">Helms</persName>’ briefing only)</item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss>
                    </item>
                    <item>Maj. Gen. <persName corresp="#p_HAM1">Alexander Haig</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_KRT1">Richard Kennedy</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_NJD1">John Negroponte</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName>Mark Wandler</persName>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <pb facs="0266" n="223" xml:id="pg_223"/>
                <p rend="center">SUMMARY OF CONCLUSIONS</p>
                <p>It was agreed that: <list>
                        <item>—Preparations would be made for a resumption of the leaflet campaign
                            in North Vietnam, but the decision to go ahead with the campaign will be
                            made later.</item>
                        <item>—Messages—similar to the one sent to Thailand—will be sent to Japan,
                            Australia, New Zealand, and Korea, giving those countries a sense of our
                            involvement in the current crisis.<note n="2" xml:id="d66fn2">According
                                to the minutes of the meeting, regarding the messages to the allies,
                                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> said the
                                following to his <gloss target="#t_WSAG1">WSAG</gloss> colleagues:
                                “Our line has to be made very clear: the North Vietnamese offensive
                                is in flagrant violation of the 1954 Geneva Accords on the <gloss
                                    target="#t_DMZ1">DMZ</gloss> and the 1968 understandings on the
                                bombing halt. That should be in the message, and it should be our
                                press line.” See message 58624 to Bangkok, April 6, printed in <ref
                                    target="frus1969-76v20#d159">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1969–1976, volume XX,
                                    Southeast Asia, 1969–1972, Document 159</ref>.</note>
                        </item>
                        <item>—The <gloss target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss> study on North Vietnamese
                            logistical operations in and near the <gloss target="#t_DMZ1"
                                >DMZ</gloss>, especially the construction of four new roads through
                            the <gloss target="#t_DMZ1">DMZ</gloss>, provides useful background
                                information.<note n="3" xml:id="d66fn3">Not found.</note> The State
                            Department spokesman should discuss the subject at his briefing
                            today.</item>
                        <item>—We can confirm the movements of units, once the movements have been
                            completed. We should not say anything about additional air authorities
                            or limits on our actions. If questioned, we should say we are attacking
                            military targets which support the North Vietnamese violations of the
                                <gloss target="#t_DMZ1">DMZ</gloss> and which are directly related
                            to the battle in South Vietnam.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>[Omitted here are the minutes of the meeting.]</p>
            </div>
